INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('inicio','en', 'There is no good straight line through the streets of La Alberca. The roads curve, the lines of the façades are broken and it is easy to get lost in its streets, paths and alleys that go up, down or criss-cross. From time to time, they offer the surprise of a fountain where you can sit down, have a good drink of water and admire the beauty of the surrounding houses.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('inicio','en', 'Some say that its urban structure is that of a Jewish quarter, due to the labyrinthine and secret nature of its streets, but others, on walking through the town, have associated it with the suburbs of Damascus. It is not in vain that its cobbled streets and wooden and stone buildings made it the first village in Spain to be declared a National Historic-Artistic Monument in 1940.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('exterior','en', 'The facades of the houses in La Alberca are strange and daring at the same time. Firstly, the ground floor: a wall of mouldy granite is created with granite ashlars or irregular stones joined with mortar, where two gates open: a narrow one that gives access to the upper floors of the house, and a wider one, destined to close the stable.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('exterior','en', 'There are houses whose access is at street level, but there are residences whose door is elevated, accessed by means of granite stairs, known as conventinos. The stable door, known as the vallipuerta, always opens inwards and to the right, as it was used so that when the rider dismounted the horse, he could access the stable without any problem.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('exterior','en', 'The rest of the house is built on the ground floor: a first and second floor and an outbuilding. These floors are supported by thick chestnut beams, enclosed by geometric wooden frames filled with stone or adobe. Each of the houses juts out from the previous one, which means that, as the house rises, the house juts out, giving the sensation that the upper floors are supported in the air.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('interior','en', 'The stable is where the everyday animals lived: mules, goats, chickens, pigs, etc. The animals played a fundamental role in that life: not only did they serve as food, but they were also an indispensable source of heat thanks to which the house was kept warm in a society in which there was no electricity, heating or running water.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('interior','en', 'Straw and fodder for the animals was stored under the staircase, and the bottom of the stable could be used as a store for manure or as a cellar for storing wine and oil during the grape and olive harvesting season. They also took advantage of this space to store their valuable belongings in the tinaja del oro, a small safe that all the houses had in the stable.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('interior','en', 'On the first floor were the most intimate and very important rooms in the Albercan house: the diary room and the good room. Both were large rooms where there could be one or more bedrooms. The sala de diario was more humble, where the family slept. The good room was a more special room, since it was where the events that marked the lives of the albercanos took place: the birth, the celebration of the christening feast, the wedding banquet, the death and the wake of the deceased...');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('interior','en', 'The first floor was where the daily life of the house took place. It housed the kitchen, the campo casa, a spacious room that was used as a landing after climbing the steep uneven wooden steps to the upper floor of the house and to store all the fruit harvested from the fields, the salaero room, where the chorizos and loins were prepared and the hams were salted, the pantry and a pair of rooms with an alcove each.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('interior','en', 'Finally, the sobrao. This floor used to have several uses: some houses that did not have a chimney on other floors used this room to put the oven where bread was baked, taking advantage of the roof for the smoke outlet.  The sobrao was also used as a drying room to dry chestnuts or hams, or as a storehouse to keep firewood or other utensils and products less used on a daily basis.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('inscripciones','en', 'On the lintel of the entrance of some houses we can find engravings with the date of construction of the house (mainly XVII-XVIII), accompanied by invocations to the Virgin Mary, crosses, some pontifical coats of arms or religious orders, and even the palm and sword of the old Holy Inquisition.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('inscripciones','en', 'La Alberca served as a refuge for Jewish converts, who, in order to avoid reprisals against them and their families, engraved the lintels of their houses, demonstrating the authenticity of their conversion to the community and the Inquisitorial vigilance.');
INSERT INTO arquitectura (catArqui, idioma, descrArqui) VALUES ('inscripciones','en', 'As a curiosity, next to the Plaza Mayor, in Calle del Tablado, is the lintel with the oldest date in the whole complex: 1613. Next to it are the initials JHS (Jesus, Man, Saviour).');
