INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'limónserrano', 'Limón serrano is a surprising dish, as, despite being a cold dish, it turns out to be a winter recipe. It is believed to be of Jewish origin, which fits in perfectly with the historical past of the Sierra de Francia, although nowadays its consumption is linked to Christian festivities. In La Alberca it was traditionally eaten for breakfast on Holy Thursdays, although it is also traditionally eaten during carnival celebrations.', '4 oranges,2 lemons,4 eggs,1 clove of garlic,Paprika,4 choricillos,Red wine,Olive oil', '1.Peel the oranges and lemons, remove the white skins and cut them into pieces.--2.Peel and crush the garlic and add it to the orange and lemon pieces.--3. Add a good splash of red wine to taste to the previous mixture.--4. Cut the choricillos into slices and fry them in a frying pan with a little olive oil. Once lightly browned, add them to the rest of the ingredients.--5. Add more oil to the pan and fry the eggs. Once fried, add them on top of the warm salad. Add salt to taste and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'cabritocuchifrito', 'If there is one way to enjoy a good suckling kid, it is to make it cuchifrito. This is a very typical recipe from the Sierra de Francia and the province of Salamanca. It is also a very simple recipe that does not require a great deal of culinary knowledge and does not take too long to prepare, which makes it the ideal recipe for beginner cooks and lovers of mountain gastronomy.', '1 kg kid,4 cloves of garlic,2 bay leaves,2 glasses of white wine,Sweet paprika,Thyme,1 boiled egg,Potatoes,Olive oil,Salt.', '1. Cut the kid into small pieces and season to taste with salt, olive oil, a spoonful of sweet paprika, thyme and a glass of white wine. Leave to macerate for 2 hours.--2. In a frying pan with plenty of oil, add the chopped garlic, bay leaves, a little paprika and thyme. When the oil is hot, add the pieces of kid and fry until golden brown.--3. Once the pieces of kid are golden brown, add a small glass of white wine to the pan, increase the heat and leave to reduce for 10 minutes, covering the pan.--4. Once the 10 minutes have elapsed, remove the kid from the pan and serve with slices of boiled or fried potatoes (to taste) and hard-boiled egg.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'zorongollo', 'Few words sound as traditional as "zorongollo". This is a very special salad of roasted peppers because, unlike other salads, this one does not have to be eaten freshly made, but must be left to rest so that the onion, the main ingredient of the dish, softens, softens its flavour and takes on the colour of the juice of the roasted peppers. It is a dish that is eaten especially in summer, and is a good accompaniment to grilled meat and fish.', '¾ red peppers,½ dried onion,2 ripe tomatoes,1 clove of garlic,Olive oil,Salt,Wine vinegar', '1. Wash the red peppers and tomatoes thoroughly, brush them with olive oil, wrap the tomatoes in aluminium foil and place everything on a baking tray.--2. Next, roast both the peppers and the tomatoes. To do this, preheat the oven to 200ºC. Once hot, place the tray prepared in the previous step at medium height for 45-50 minutes.--TIP: After 25-30 minutes, turn the peppers over.--3. When the tray is removed, transfer the peppers and tomatoes to a serving dish and cover them well so that they can "sweat" for approximately 30 minutes, in order to remove the skin easily. Reserve the juice from the roasted peppers.--4. Once the 30 minutes have elapsed, remove the skin and seeds and dice the tomatoes and cut the peppers into strips.--5. Peel the onion and garlic and chop them. Mix all the ingredients together and dress with olive oil, wine vinegar, salt and some of the juice from the roasted peppers. Leave the salad to rest for 18-24 hours in the refrigerator and serve.--');
INSERT INTO gastronomia (catGastro, idioma, nombreReceta, descrGastro, ingrReceta, pasosReceta) VALUES ('receta', 'en', 'lechefrita', 'POR HACER--', '120g sugar,3 eggs,1l milk,120g cornflour,120g cornstarch,Oil for frying,Sugar for coating,1 stick cinnamon,1 teaspoon vanilla,50g flour,1 lemon peel,1 orange peel', '1. Set aside approximately 1 glass of milk and reserve. Add the rest of the milk to a saucepan together with the orange and lemon peel, cinnamon and sugar. Bring to the boil for approximately 10 minutes and remove from the heat.--2. Add the cornflour and vanilla to the reserved glass of milk and stir. Strain all the milk fried in the previous step into a saucepan and add the glass of milk with the cornflour.--3. Stir the prepared mixture and bring to the heat to thicken. Remove the saucepan from the heat when a very creamy texture has been obtained.--4. Pour the mixture into a tray and cover with plastic wrap to prevent it from crusting. Leave to cool completely in the fridge overnight.--5. Once cold, cut the fried milk into portions of the size you want. Beat the eggs and dip the fried milk portions in flour and beaten egg.--6. Heat plenty of oil in a frying pan and fry the fried milk until golden brown on all sides. Once fried, remove to a plate with absorbent paper.--7. Dredge the portions in sugar and serve.--');
